{{Other uses}} {{multiple issues| {{globalize/United States|date=December 2013}} {{refimprove|date=December 2013}} {{citation style|date=November 2018}} }} {{Infobox occupation | name = Bounty hunter | image = | imagesize = 225px | alt = | caption = | official_names = | type = | activity_sector = [[United States]], [[Philippines]] | competencies = | formation = | employment_field = [[Law enforcement]] | related_occupation = [[Bail bondsman]], [[Thief-taker]], [[Slave catcher]] }}
A '''bounty hunter''' is a person who captures [[fugitive]]s for a [[bounty (reward)|bounty]]. The occupation, also known as bail enforcement agent, bail agent, recovery agent, bail recovery agents, or fugitive recovery agent, has historically existed in many parts of the world. However, today, it is found almost exclusively in most of the [[United States]] and its former commonwealth, the [[Philippines]], as the practice is illegal under the laws of most other countries. Illinois, Kentucky, Oregon and Wisconsin have outlawed commercial bail bonds.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/29/us/29bail.html?pagewanted=all&_r=1 ''Illegal Globally, Bail for Profit Remains in U.S.''], Adam Liptak, 29Jan2008, The New York Times</ref>
==United States== ===History=== ====The Old West==== In 1873, the [[Supreme Court]] ruled that bounty hunters were a part of the U.S. law enforcement system with a decision in ''[[Taylor v. Taintor]]'':<ref>p. 367 Dempsey, John ''Introduction to Private Security'' Cengage Learning, 23 Mar 2010</ref>
{{quotation|When the bail is given, the principal is regarded as delivered to the custody of his sureties. Their domain is a continuance of the original imprisonment. Whenever they choose to do so, they may seize him and deliver him up to his discharge; and if it cannot be done at once, they may imprison him until it can be done. They may exercise their rights in person or by agent. They may pursue him into another state; may arrest him on the Sabbath; and if necessary, may break and enter his house for that purpose. The seizure is not made by virtue of due process. None is needed. It is likened to the arrest by the [[sheriff]] of an escaped prisoner.}}
====Modern times==== In modern times, bounty hunters are known as bail enforcement agent or fugitive recovery agents ([[bail bondsman|bail bondsmen]]), and carry out arrests mostly of those who have skipped bail.<ref name="insi_Bail">{{cite web| title = Bail Enforcement Agent| website= Inside Jobs| accessdate = 2015-07-08| url = http://www.insidejobs.com/careers/bail-enforcement-agent}}</ref><ref name="dos._NYSD">{{cite web| title = NYS Division of Licensing Services| website= dos.ny.gov| accessdate = 2015-07-08| url = http://www.dos.ny.gov/licensing/bailagent/bailagent.html}}</ref> The term "bounty hunting" is neither often used nor liked by many in the profession due to its historical associations.{{citation needed|reason=|date=March 2016}}
Bounty hunters are sometimes misleadingly called ''[[skiptracer|skiptracers]]'', where ''skiptracing'' is searching for an individual through less direct methods than active pursuit and apprehension.
When undertaking arrest warrants, agents may wear [[Bulletproof vest|bullet-resistant vests]], badges, and other clothing bearing the inscription "bail enforcement agent" or similar titles.<ref name="youtube.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s-yN7LJcxZA |work=Secrets Of A Modern Day Bounty Hunter|title=Tools Of The Trade |publisher=YouTube |date=2009-05-08 |accessdate=2016-12-20}}</ref> Many agents also use [[two-way radio]]s to communicate with each other.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}} Many agents arm themselves with firearms; or sometimes with less lethal weapons, such as [[taser|tasers]],<ref name="youtube.com" /> [[Baton (law enforcement)|batons]], [[tear gas]] ([[CS gas]], [[pepper spray]])<ref name="youtube.com" /> or [[pepper-spray projectile|pepper spray projectiles]].{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}
In the United States, the National Association of Fugitive Recovery Agents is the professional association representing this industry.{{citation needed|date=March 2016|reason=http://www.fugitive-recovery.org/media.htm}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fugitive-recovery.org/media.htm|title=Media Inquiries|last=|first=|date=September 30, 2016|website=NAFRA|publisher=|access-date=September 30, 2016}}</ref>
===Practice=== Most bounty hunters are employed by [[Bail bondsman|bail bondsmen]]: the bounty hunter is usually paid about 18% of the total [[bail]] amount, but this commission can vary on an individual, case-by-case basis; usually depending upon the difficulty level of the assignment and the approach used to exonerate the bail bond. If the fugitive eludes bail, the bondsman, not the bounty hunter, is responsible for 100% of the total bail amount. This is a way of ensuring clients arrive at trial. As of 2003, bounty hunters claimed to catch 31,500 bail jumpers per year, about 90% of people who jump bail.<ref name="BBC20070922">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/3003886.stm|title=Above the law: US bounty hunters|first=Rachel|last=Clarke|date=19 June 2003|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=2007-09-22}}</ref>
Bounty hunters have varying levels of authority in their duties with regard to their targets depending on which states they operate in. Barring restrictions applicable state by state, a bounty hunter may enter the fugitive's [[private property]] without a [[Warrant (law)|warrant]] in order to execute a re-arrest. A bounty hunter cannot, however, enter the property of anyone other than the fugitive without a warrant or the owner's permission.{{citation needed|reason=|date=March 2016}}
In some states, bounty hunters do not undergo any formal training,<ref name="Bounty Hunter Blitz">{{cite web|url=http://www.learnbountyhunting.com/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407091817/http://www.learnbountyhunting.com/|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2016-04-07|title=Bounty Hunter Blitz|publisher=COA Org|accessdate=2011-02-27}} </ref> and are generally unlicensed, only requiring sanction from a bail bondsman to operate. In other states, however, they are held to varying standards of training and [[license]]. State legal requirements are often imposed on out-of-state bounty hunters, so a fugitive could temporarily escape rearrest by entering a state in which the bail agent has limited or no jurisdiction.{{citation needed|reason=|date=March 2016}}
===Laws and regulation=== In the United States legal system, the 1873 [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]] case ''[[Taylor v. Taintor]]'', 16 Wall (83 U.S. 366, 21 L.Ed. 287), is cited as having established that the person into whose custody an accused is remanded as part of the accuser's [[bail]] has sweeping rights to that person.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Appleman | first=Laura I. | date=June 1, 2012 | title=Justice in the Shadowlands: Pretrial Detention, Punishment, & the Sixth Amendment | work=[[Washington and Lee Law Review]] | volume=69 | page=1308 | url=http://scholarlycommons.law.wlu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=4288&context=wlulr | access-date=August 15, 2017}}</ref> Though this may have been accurate at the time the decision was reached, the portion cited was [[obiter dictum]] and has no binding precedential value.<ref>{{cite court | litigants=Walker v. Commonwealth | vol=127 | reporter=S.W.3d | opinion=596 | pinpoint=605 | court=Ky. | date=2004 | url=https://advance.lexis.com/api/document/collection/cases/id/4BRS-TKY0-0039-44RB-00000-00?cite=127%20S.W.3d%20596&context=1000516 | access-date=August 15, 2017}}</ref>
As of 2008, four states, [[Illinois]], [[Kentucky]], [[Oregon]], and [[Wisconsin]] prohibited the practice, as they have abolished commercial bail bonds and banned the commercial bail bonds industry within their borders.<ref name=nyt>Adam Liptak [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/29/us/29bail.html?pagewanted=all&_r=1 Illegal Globally, Bail for Profit Remains in U.S.], New York Times, 29 January 2008</ref> As of 2012, [[Nebraska]] and [[Maine]] similarly prohibit surety bail bonds.<ref name="Bail Bonds Information">[http://bailbondsnetwork.com/ Bail Bonds Information], Bail Bonds Agent Directory by Bail Bonds Network, n.d., Retrieved 2012-07-18.</ref> Some states such as Texas and California require a license to engage in bounty hunting while others may have no restrictions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.securityguardtrainingtips.com/Bounty-Hunter-State-Requirements.php|title=Bounty Hunter License For Each State.|website=www.securityguardtrainingtips.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-22}}</ref>
There have been some states that have rolled out specific laws that govern bounty hunting. For example, Minnesota says that you cannot drive a white, black, maroon, or dark green vehicle. They also outline what you can wear. The statute states that you can wear any colors that are not reserved for the police in the state. For example, [https://www.revisor.mn.gov/statutes/2017/cite/626.88 The Minnesota Highway Patrol wears maroon uniforms. The city police departments along with county sheriff's and their deputies are all blue brown or green, and the Minnesota DNR is green.] Therefore, a bounty hunter in the state in of Minnesota can wear any colors that are not already listed above. It is recommended that anyone looking to work in this field be knowledgeable of these laws before they hit the streets. ====Connecticut==== The State of [[Connecticut]] has a detailed licensing process which requires any person who wants to engage in the business as a bail enforcement agent (bounty hunter) to first obtain a professional license from the Commissioner of Public Safety; specifically detailing that "No person shall, as surety on a bond in a criminal proceeding or as an agent of such surety, engage in the business of taking or attempting to take into custody the principal on the bond who has failed to appear in court and for whom a re-arrest warrant or capias has been issued unless such person is licensed as a bail enforcement agent". Connecticut has strict standards which require Bail Enforcement Agents to pass an extensive background check and, while engaging in fugitive recovery operations, be uniformed, notify the local police barrack, wear a badge, and only carry licensed and approved firearms, including handguns and long guns which are permitted. Recently [[Connecticut State Police]] converted its Bail Enforcement Agent licensing unit to reflect the important role Bail Enforcement Agents play in the Connecticut criminal justice system; placing them in the newly defined Department of Emergency Services and Public Protection.<ref name="Connecticut Department of Emergency Services & Public Protection">{{cite web|url=http://www.ct.gov/dps/cwp/view.asp?a=2158&q=294480|title=Special Licensing and Firearms: Bail Enforcement Agents (BEA)|publisher=Connecticut Department of Emergency Services & Public Protection|accessdate=2011-01-27}}</ref>
Several schools in Connecticut have obtained certification by the Connecticut State Police to pre-license Bail Enforcement Agents in a minimum of 20 hours of criminal justice training and a minimum of eight hours of firearms training. Some of the more advanced schools offer specialized training in the area of tactical firearms to prepare BEAs for conducting dangerous recovery operations.<ref name="Tactical Recovery Network">{{cite web|url=http://www.recoverycontractors.org/Tactical-Fireams-Training.html|title=Tactical Firearms Training|publisher=Tactical Recovery Network|accessdate=2012-05-17}}</ref>
====Florida==== In [[Florida]], a bounty hunter must obtain a "limited surety agent" license from the [[Florida Department of Financial Services]], Bureau of Agent and Agency Licensing, in order to legally apprehend bail fugitives.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Temporary Resident Limited Surety Agent|url = http://www.myfloridacfo.com/Division/Agents/Licensure/General/docs/T2-35.htm|website = Jimmy Patrol, Florida's Chief Financial Officer|access-date = 2017-08-21}}</ref>
====Louisiana==== [[Louisiana]] requires bounty hunters to wear clothing identifying them as such.<ref name="ABClaws">{{cite web|url=http://www.americanbailcoalition.com/new_html/Bounty%20Hunter%20Laws.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021207171145/http://americanbailcoalition.com/new_html/Bounty%20Hunter%20Laws.htm|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2002-12-07|title=Bounty Hunter laws|publisher=americanbailcoalition.com|first=Jonathan|last=Drimmer|accessdate=2007-09-22|df=}} </ref>
====Nevada==== A [[Nevada]] bounty hunter is referred to as a bail enforcement agent or bail enforcement solicitor. It requires a minimum 20 hours of training, passing examinations and obtaining a bail enforcement agent license by the Nevada Division of Insurance within nine months of employment as a bail agent.<ref>[http://doi.nv.gov/Licensing/Licensing-with-Special-Requirements/Bail-Agent-Solicitor-Instructions/ Bail Agent/Solicitor Individual Instructions] Nevada Division of Insurance, 2013, retrieved 24 March 2018</ref><ref>[http://www.howtobecomeabountyhunter.com/states/nevada/ How to Become a Bounty Hunter in Nevada] HowToBecomeABountyHunter.com, n.d.</ref> To acquire such license one must be at least 21 years old, a United States citizen, have a high school diploma or equivalent, undergo the extensive training and pass a state examination.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.leg.state.nv.us/nrs/nrs-697.html|title=NRS: CHAPTER 697 - BUSINESSES RELATED TO BAIL|website=www.leg.state.nv.us|access-date=2017-03-22}}</ref>{{citation needed|reason=|date=March 2016}}
====Texas==== A [[Texas]] bounty hunter is required to be a peace officer, Level III (armed) [[security officer]], or a [[private investigator]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fugitiverecovery.com/bail-bond-laws/directory/texas/|title=Texas - Bail Bond and Bounty Hunter Laws|website=fugitiverecovery.com|access-date=2017-03-22}}</ref><ref>[http://bountyhunters.uslegal.com/licensing-and-arrest-authority-of-bounty-hunters/texas/] USLegal, Inc, n.d., retrieved 24 March 2016</ref>{{better source|date=March 2016}}
===International action by U.S. bounty hunters=== Bounty hunters may run into serious legal problems if they try to apprehend fugitives outside the United States, where laws treat the re-arrest of any fugitive by private persons as [[kidnapping]], or the bail agent may incur the punishments of some other serious crime if local ''and'' international laws are broken by them.{{clarify|date=October 2011|reason=international law usually is talking about treaties or crimes against humanity}} While the United States government generally allows the activities of bounty hunters within the United States, the governments in other [[sovereignty#Sovereignty in international law|sovereign]] nations consider them a felony.<ref name="Covey2003" />
Bounty hunter [[Duane Chapman|Duane "Dog" Chapman]], star of the TV series ''[[Dog the Bounty Hunter]]'', was arrested in [[Mexico]] after he apprehended the multi-millionaire rapist and fugitive [[Andrew Luster]]. Chapman was subsequently released and returned to the U.S.<ref name="BBC20070922" /> but was later declared a fugitive by a Mexican prosecutor and was subsequently arrested in the United States to be extradited back to Mexico. Chapman has maintained that under Mexico's citizen arrest law, he and his crew acted under proper policy.{{citation needed|reason=|date=March 2016}}
Daniel Kear of [[Fairfax, Virginia]] pursued and apprehended [[Sidney Jaffe]] at a residence in [[Canada]] and returned him to [[Florida]] to face trial. Kear was extradited to Canada in 1983, and convicted of kidnapping.<ref name="Covey2003">{{cite web|url=http://writ.news.findlaw.com/commentary/20030710_covey.html|title=The Perils of Bounty hunting|first=Russell|last=Covey|date=July 10, 2003|publisher=findlaw.com|accessdate=2007-09-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Canadian, kidnapped, to stand trial in Florida, is free on bond |author= |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/10/12/us/canadian-kidnapped-to-stand-trial-in-florida-is-free-on-bond.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 12, 1983 |accessdate=2 August 2013}}</ref>
Several bounty hunters have been arrested for killing the fugitive or apprehending the wrong individuals, mistaking innocent people for fugitives.<ref name="Bounty Hunters Arrested for Kidnapping">{{cite web |url=http://www.kake.com/findit/wednesdayheadlines/41835062.html |title=Bounty Hunters Arrested for Kidnapping |first=Deb |last=Farris |publisher=KAKE TV |accessdate=2009-07-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090801072748/http://www.kake.com/findit/wednesdayheadlines/41835062.html |archivedate=2009-08-01 |df= }}</ref>
Unlike police officers, they have no legal protections against injuries to non-fugitives and few legal protections against injuries to their targets.{{citation needed|reason=|date=March 2016}}
In a Texas case, bounty hunters Richard James and his partner DG Pearson were arrested in 2001 for felony charges during an arrest. The charges were levied by the fugitive and his family, but were later dismissed against the hunters after the fugitive's wife shot a deputy sheriff in another arrest attempt of the fugitive by the county sheriff's department. The hunters sued the fugitive and family, winning the civil suit for [[malicious prosecution]] with a judgment amount of $1.5 million.{{citation needed|date=August 2011}}
==Rhodesia== During the [[Rhodesian Bush War]], [[Cattle raiding|cattle rustling]] reached epidemic proportions in the late 1970s. This was part of a twofold strategy of the [[guerrilla]]s against the white minority government in [[Harare|Salisbury]]. First, it led to starvation in the Tribal Trust Lands; second, it negatively affected the economy of [[Rhodesia]] (now [[Zimbabwe]]). Because the army and the [[British South Africa Police]] were overstretched on three fronts, [[mercenary|mercenaries]] were hired to confront the rustlers. They were called "Range Detectives", and most of them were [[Vietnam veteran]]s, some of them members of [[The Crippled Eagles]]. Payment was roughly seven [[Rhodesian dollar]]s a day, and a 750 Rhodesian dollar bonus for each rustler caught.<ref>Earp, Wyatt, Jr.: "Pros at work: Bounty hunting in Africa", ''[[Soldier of Fortune (magazine)|Soldier of Fortune]]'', March 1977.</ref>
